This paper is primarily focused on machine learning and optimization, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also deals with adversarial examples, which are a common topic in the fields of computer security and cryptography, making cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) another likely sub-category. The use of decision trees and tree-based models suggests that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) are also possible sub-categories. Finally, the paper includes experimental results on real-world datasets, which suggests that cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) may also be a relevant sub-category.
